	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade policy: Eastern and Southern Africa free-trade area starts to take shape</h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>EAC, SADC and COMESA are reported to have created a draft agreement paving the way to the formation of a free-trade area (FTA) linking the member states. Mr Sindiso Ngwenya, the secretary-general of COMESA, is reported as saying that ‘The draft contains proposals on common rules that would govern the trade regimes and bring them together into a seamless platform.’ It includes 14 annexes that deal with rules of origin, intellectual property rights, and dispute settlement, among other provisions.</p><p>The draft is a major step forward following the decision of principle taken two years ago to create the ‘super FTA’, said to cover a market of 527 million people. Any economic integration scheme that reduces barriers to trade among members has to grapple with the differing interests of the more and less developed members. Kenya, which together with South Africa and Egypt is more likely to be able to boost a wide range of exports to partners, is reported to have made proposals to accommodate such problems. These include a set of transitional measures and adjustment support to the more disadvantaged members of the proposed US$624 billion FTA.</p><p>The FTA will also need to accommodate differences in the pre-existing trade agreements of members, including the interim Economic Partnership Agreements (IEPAs) signed by some but not by others. Adbulrazaq Ali, Permanent Secretary at the Kenya Ministry of Trade is reported to have told a meeting of CEOs of business organisations from eastern and southern Africa (ESA) that these differences would need to be included in the transitional measures. </p><p>This agreement comes at a time when TRALAC, the Trade Law Centre for Southern Africa, reports that regional economic communities (RECs) ‘especially in Africa, are not fully meeting their visions, not fulfilling all their promises, and not yet delivering the desired outcomes and services to the members of their communities and states.’ In its 2009 Yearbook TRALAC argues that ‘regional integration and strong RECs in general and a strong SADC in particular could pay dividends – especially in the context of challenges which go far beyond the boundaries and the resources of individual states and regions’, such as climate change and the financial crisis, which ‘require the united efforts of regional blocs and continents.’ But ominously the Yearbook reports that while ‘for the sake of regional integration, certain national interests and unilateral efforts should be abandoned’, in practice ‘the opposite seems to drive many of the stakeholders.’</p><p>Taku Fundira, a TRALAC trade researcher, identifies ‘the issue of sensitive products that will be exempt from liberalisation’ as a major bone of contention when creating an expanded regional trading arrangement. He argues that it is important ‘to ensure that countries are encouraged to base their selection on genuine public policy objectives’, otherwise the sensitive lists ‘are more likely to reflect protectionist interests or rent-seeking behaviour, both of which will perpetuate inefficiencies.’ </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Business Daily</i> (Nairobi), ‘African economic blocs set rules for free trade areas’, 25 August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause_id=1694&amp;news_id=91808&amp;cat_id=1026" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause...</a></p><p>TRALAC, ‘Monitoring regional integration in Southern Africa: Yearbook’, Vol. 9, 2009</p><p>
<a href="http://www.givengain.com/cause_data/images/1694/FINAL_MRI_2009_20100701.pdf" target="_self">http://www.givengain.com/cause_data/images/1694/FINAL_MRI_2009_20100701.pdf</a></p><p>TRALAC, commentary on ‘the need for tariff rationalisation and common criteria for determining sensitive products within the proposed tripartite COMESA-SADC-EAC FTA’, 25 August 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause_id=1694&amp;news_id=91809&amp;cat_id=1026" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Globally, most regional economic communities (RECs) have failed, either breaking up altogether or stalling at a much lower level of integration than their founders had envisaged because of differences in interests among members. This problem has been reflected in SADC’s goal of moving beyond an FTA to a customs union: this will require an accommodation between the interests of some members (most notably South Africa) to develop their regional manufactured and processed agricultural exports (facilitated by a high common external tariff [CET] on these goods), and the interests of the net regional importers to obtain the goods from the most competitive global source. </p><p>The fact that some but not all states of Eastern and Southern Africa have signed IEPAs has created a further problem for the customs union plans of COMESA and SADC. The CET must apply to all members – so either those states that have agreed to liberalise imports from the EU must backtrack, or those outside the EPA will have to accept a zero CET on many goods imported from Europe. </p><p>The goal of creating a single FTA for all of Eastern and Southern Africa, rather than the more complex customs union, is an appropriate response to these challenges, as it avoids the need to agree a CET. However, this simply reduces the immediate need to address discrepancies in tariff treatment, rather than eliminating this underlying problem. Only when details emerge of the transitional measures mentioned by Adbulrazaq Ali and of the agreed rules of origin will it be possible to gauge the likelihood of success.</p>
		</div>
		
